body:
### Bug description

code below is not thread safe and leads to multiple CosmosClients created
```csharp
dbContext.Database.GetCosmosClient();
```

Multiple clients created leads to constant resource fighting between clients and 100% CPU on a client which quickly leads to 503 errros and service down:
```
Response status code does not indicate success: ServiceUnavailable (503); 
Substatus: 20005; 
Reason: (The request failed because the client was unable to establish connections to 1 endpoints across 1 regions. 
The client CPU has thread starvation.
```

At first we reproduced in our changefeeds where we were doing batch Patch operations. Our service was using 100% CPU and spit 503s non-stop

After checking CosmosDiagnostic I found 27 active CosmosClients:
```
            "NumberOfClientsCreated": 27,
            "NumberOfActiveClients": 27,
            "ConnectionMode": "Direct",
            "User Agent": "cosmos-netstandard-sdk/3.52.0|1|X64|Microsoft Windows 10.0.26100|.NET 8.0.19|N|",
            "ConnectionConfig": {
                "gw": "(cps:50, urto:6, p:False, httpf: False)",
                "rntbd": "(cto: 5, icto: -1, mrpc: 30, mcpe: 65535, erd: True, pr: ReuseUnicastPort)",
                "other": "(ed:False, be:False)"
            },
```

Then I patched it locally with static lock object
<img width="1351" height="296" alt="Image" src="https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/3424e336-942c-4978-99f2-f5beb74d469a" />

Which actually helped!

So then I constructed a simple test to reproduce the problem:
```csharp
public static T GetStaticField<T>(Type t, string name)
    {
        const BindingFlags flags =
            BindingFlags.Static | BindingFlags.NonPublic | BindingFlags.Public;

        var field = t.GetField(name, flags)
            ?? throw new MissingFieldException(t.FullName, name);

        return (T)field.GetValue(null)!;
    }

    [TestMethod]
    public void Foo()
    {
        var services = new ServiceCollection();
        services.AddDbContextFactory<AnyContext>(options =>
        {
            options
                .UseCosmos(
                    connectionString,
                    databaseName: dbName
                )
                .UseQueryTrackingBehavior(QueryTrackingBehavior.NoTracking)
                .EnableDetailedErrors();
            services.AddSingleton(options);
        });

        var serviceProvider = services.BuildServiceProvider();

        var tasks = new List<Task>();
        for (int i = 0; i < 100; i++)
        {
            tasks.Add(DoWork());
        }
        Task.WaitAll(tasks.ToArray());

        int created = GetStaticField<int>(typeof(CosmosClient), "numberOfClientsCreated");
        int active  = GetStaticField<int>(typeof(CosmosClient), "NumberOfActiveClients");
        Console.WriteLine($"created={created} active={active}");
        return;

        async Task DoWork()
        {
            await Task.Yield();
            var fac = serviceProvider.GetRequiredService<IDbContextFactory<AnyContext>>();
            await using var ctx = await fac.CreateDbContextAsync();
            // await using var ctx = serviceProvider.GetRequiredService<AnyContext>();
            var client = ctx.Database.GetCosmosClient();
            var container = client.GetContainer(dbName, containerName);
            try
            {
                var item = await container.ReadItemAsync<AnyModel>("anyId",
                    new PartitionKey("AnyPartition"));
                Console.WriteLine(item.ToString());
            }
            catch
            {
                // ignored
            }
        }
    }
```

And on my machine that immediately returned:
`created=32 active=32`

